Europe needs immigration to restart.
Brussels—More than 900 migrants attempting to reach Europe have drowned in the Mediterranean this year.
At the same time, the rescue ships Open Arms and Ocean Viking were searching for a safe port all summer where passengers on board could disembark.
Greece's Lesbos Island refugee and migrant camps are overcrowded, and conditions at Libya's other reception centers are similarly dire.
Turkey tore up a 2016 agreement to block migrants entering the EU.
Despite the desire of Europe to help migrants and respect international law, it does not want to be overpopulated.
In 2015-16, the influx of refugees and migrants into the European Union surged — — many were fleeing the Syrian war — — this had a huge impact on trust within the EU.
A massive influx of migrants has eroded the government's confidence in managing external borders and asylum, and also highlighted the futility of cooperating with countries of origin of migrants.
Therefore, immigration has become a political football, a magnet for populists.
Under the leadership of President von der Leyen, the new European Commission must regain control of the migration issue while respecting the dignity of those seeking a better life.
For this purpose, the EU needs to re-establish guidelines in four areas and mobilise member states to act in the interests of Europe.
First, the EU must urgently safeguard its external borders, which is a prerequisite for keeping its internal borders open.
In any country where people are free to move within the country, including the United States, India, China, Switzerland, and Russia, among others, they will not outsource border control to a particular state or region.
Managing the external borders of the European Union must be a collective task, it is also a national task.
The European Border and Coast Guard Agency Frontex must be further reinforced and should be deployed jointly with member states — including coastlines and airports.
The European Union must also relaunch Operation Sophia to combat illegal immigration in the Mediterranean.
Secondly, Europe needs to handle economic migrants and asylum seekers separately.
Mixing them together has almost led to the collapse of the protection system; separating them will help ensure that migrants concerned about their safety can make their voices heard while their rights are protected.
Meeting the EU's true economic and social needs requires effective blue card or green card policies for economic migrants and implementing overall migration goals.
A comprehensive policy framework that addresses all aspects of immigration cannot wait for the next crisis to be considered.
To achieve this, the EU must break the taboo.
Firstly, the number of economic migrants entering the EU labour market must be recognized as an issue of common interest.
Secondly, the policy must clearly state which immigrants are welcome.
Thirdly, member states must answer what EU help is needed to achieve a smooth migration process.
Finally, visa and work permits must be put on the table for the benefit of undocumented immigrants returning to their countries of origin.
Indeed, according to the EU treaty, each member state is required to manage its own immigration from outside the EU.
But, if the government agrees on the overall EU migration target, that would be a huge step forward.
In turn, member states can indicate the desired country of origin for economic migration and specific requirements, and receive the necessary EU budget resources to accommodate them.
This way, the right of immigration will become a privilege rather than a burden.
For example, Canada has long had an active immigration policy that selects immigrants based on factors such as the country of origin, skills, and age.
Europe can do the same.
Thirdly, the EU needs to improve its asylum system.
First and foremost, a one-size-fits-all approach to asylum seekers within the EU must be discarded.
This demand has destroyed the atmosphere within the EU, but if the border, asylum and immigration system were fully effective, it would still be feasible.
In addition, no single member state of the EU can be expected to solve the problem of illegal migration across external borders on its own.
The refugee camp is overcrowded, migrants are subjected to abuse by the authorities or are being forced northwards.
The responsibility of the first Member State that the immigrant arrives at must be supplemented by the cohesion of the European Union.
The EU must also provide experts and funding to harmonize the actions and management capacity of national asylum institutions.
Only in this way, a country's decision can be respected throughout the Schengen area, and the integrity of the border region can be ensured.
After rationalizing the behavior and management capabilities of national protection institutions, the processing procedures for protection applications can also be shared among member states.
Fourth, the EU should forge stronger win-win cooperation with the source country and transit country.
These contacts are crucial to deport migrants who have been lawfully banned from entering the EU to their country of origin.
To ensure cooperation, the EU should mobilize all diplomatic tools, including development aid and investment funds, as well as plans in the areas of security, trade, energy, agriculture, fisheries, climate action, aviation, and health.
The EU's migration goals, and skills cooperation to prepare for European jobs, can be offered to third countries that crave stable diaspora remittances.
At the same time, the European Union must tackle the root cause of immigration.
These include population explosions in sub-Saharan Africa; climate change affecting food security; outbreaks of infectious diseases; ethnic conflicts; and a lack of job opportunities.
The EU's assistance should focus on rebuilding stability and reducing risk through support for security, community resilience and good governance.
This kind of success can make investment safer, release private and domestic finance, and thereby achieve national economic growth, job creation, and provide alternatives to immigration.
The new European Commission has the opportunity to move the EU beyond its reflexive response to the migration crisis and towards more cohesive and sustained policies, whether internally or externally.
We absolutely cannot miss the opportunity.
